									<sci:arg name="ComponentHelp" type="StringType" required="false" visibility="nevershow" multi="true">
										<sci:value>100</sci:value>
										<sci:value>Adds a container (that is, a &quot;div&quot; element) that can be updated with content generated by another protocol, using AJAX</sci:value>
										<sci:value>&lt;p&gt;Use this component to create an area in a report (a &quot;container&quot;) where any existing content can be replaced with the results of another protocol without refreshing the rest of the report.  Use this component in conjunction with the &lt;a href=&quot;javascript:DoLink(&apos;{5D0F8E8E-290C-4e9c-81D1-223ACA806544}&apos;)&quot;&gt;Protocol Function&lt;/a&gt; component to provide &lt;a href=&quot;javascript:DoLink(&apos;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ajax_%28programming%29&apos;)&quot;&gt;AJAX&lt;/a&gt; functionality in reports.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Alternatively, use the container to generate &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;div&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; elements in a report that can be manipulated via JavaScript.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The Protocol Function component specifies a protocol to run when the user takes an action such as clicking a button in the original report.  When that action happens, the results of that protocol (a table, a chart, etc.) will be placed into the container defined by the Dynamic Content Container, replacing anything that is currently present.  To link a Protocol Function component to this one, set its &lt;i&gt;Dynamic Content Container ID&lt;/i&gt; to match the &lt;i&gt;Container ID&lt;/i&gt; on this component.  Multiple Protocol Function components may update the same container, and multiple pairs of Dynamic Content Container and Protocol Function components can be used in a single report.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When a protocol containing a Dynamic Content Container is run to generate a report, the container initially functions very much like a paragraph component. Any reporting content on data records piped in will be displayed inside the container.  This content can then be updated using the AJAX functionality.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The container can also be used as a general box for content, as it supports the specification of fixed width and height and provides a means to specify how oversized content is handled.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Notes:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This component is for use in HTML reports only.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The value of the &lt;i&gt;Container ID&lt;/i&gt; is output as an ID attribute. ID values should be unique within a report.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Dynamic Content Containers can be nested.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;See Also:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;javascript:DoLink(&apos;sciapps/scitegic/report/docs/reporting_basic.pdf&apos;)&quot;&gt;Report Design Essentials&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;javascript:DoLink(&apos;sciapps/scitegic/reportadv/docs/reportadv_interactive.pdf&apos;)&quot;&gt;Interactive Reporting and Form Design&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</sci:value>
										<sci:value>Generic</sci:value>
										<sci:value>One or more data records containing reporting objects</sci:value>
										<sci:value>Generic</sci:value>
										<sci:value>A data record representing the container is sent to the pass port.</sci:value>
										<sci:value>None</sci:value>
										<sci:value/>
									</sci:arg>
									<sci:arg name="Component Path" type="StringType" required="false" visibility="nevershow" multi="false">
										<sci:help>The original path within the database of this component.</sci:help>
										<sci:value>Components\Reporting and Visualization\Reporting\Web Application Development\HTML Elements\Dynamic Content Container</sci:value>
									</sci:arg>
								</sci:component>
							</sci:data>
							<sci:data object="SciTegic.ComponentJavaPlugin.1">
								<sci:component name="Dynamic Content Container" version="2">
									<sci:arg name="Container ID" type="StringType" required="false" visibility="visible" multi="false">
										<sci:help>&lt;p&gt;The ID specified here should be referenced in any &lt;a href=&quot;javascript:DoLink(&apos;{5D0F8E8E-290C-4e9c-81D1-223ACA806544}&apos;)&quot;&gt;Protocol Function&lt;/a&gt; components that will automatically insert content into this container.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To guarantee interoperability among browsers, IDs should start with a letter and consist only of letters, numbers, hyphens, underscores, colons, and periods.&lt;/p&gt;</sci:help>
									</sci:arg>
									<sci:arg name="Format" type="FormatType" required="false" visibility="visible" multi="false">
										<sci:help>&lt;p&gt;Specifies formatting to be applied to this element. Editing this parameter opens the Format Dialog.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Depending on what this Format is being applied to, options may include:
&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Font settings (e.g., Color, Size, Bold, Italic, Underline)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Border settings (e.g., Color, Style, Width)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Background settings (Color, Image)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Alignment settings&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;etc.&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Notes:&lt;/b&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Only options that are relevant for this specific Format parameter will be displayed.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Background Image: Allows you to select a background image for the reporting element. This image must be accessible to the Pipeline Pilot server. For example, there are some example images in the apps\scitegic\generic\dataroot\data\Images folder in your Pipeline Pilot installation (shortcut is &quot;generic\Images&quot; folder). To use your own images, you need to upload them to a location such as your userdir or jobdir. An easy way to do this is to use the Binary Reader component to read the file, and the Binary Writer component to save it to the chosen location. Supported image types include .gif, .jpg, .png, and .bmp.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</sci:help>
										<sci:value>700</sci:value>
									</sci:arg>
									<sci:arg name="Position" type="PositionType" required="false" visibility="visible" multi="false">
										<sci:help>&lt;p&gt;Specifies how this element is positioned. Editing this parameter opens the Position dialog, which enables you to change margins, paddings, width, and height.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If the Overflow Behavior is set to &quot;Resize Container&quot;, any width and height information will be ignored, as the container will resize itself to its contents.&lt;/p&gt;</sci:help>
									</sci:arg>
									<sci:arg name="Overflow Behavior" type="StringType" required="true" visibility="visible" multi="false">
										<sci:help>&lt;p&gt;How the container should treat oversized content inserted into the container:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;i&gt;Show scrollbars as necessary&lt;/i&gt;: If the content placed inside the container is larger than the size of the container (if an exact width or height are specified), then scrollbars will be shown to allow the user to scroll through all content.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;i&gt;Clipped&lt;/i&gt;: If the content placed inside the container is larger than the size of the container (if an exact width and height are specified), then any content overflowing the container will be clipped off, and no scrollbars will appear.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;i&gt;Resize to Content&lt;/i&gt;: Resizes the container to tightly fit the current content (also applies to initial content). Any width and height information specified in the Position parameter will be ignored.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;</sci:help>
										<sci:legalval selected="true">Show Scrollbars as Necessary</sci:legalval>
										<sci:legalval>Clipped</sci:legalval>
										<sci:legalval>Resize to Content</sci:legalval>
									</sci:arg>
									<sci:arg name="Links and Actions" type="GroupType" required="false" visibility="visible" multi="false" expanded="true" uimpl="false">
										<sci:help>Links and actions to be applied to the report element produced by this component.</sci:help>
										<sci:member>Link Target</sci:member>
										<sci:member>HTML Attributes</sci:member>
										<sci:member>Tooltip</sci:member>
									</sci:arg>
									<sci:arg name="Link Target" type="StringType" required="false" visibility="visible" multi="false" uimpl="false">
										<sci:help>Sets this element as the destination for links from other elements in the report. The value of &lt;i&gt;Link Target&lt;/i&gt; can be text or a property name, and should match the value of &lt;i&gt;Link&lt;/i&gt; in another report component.  In the resulting report, when the element with &lt;i&gt;Link&lt;/i&gt; is clicked, the element with the matching &lt;i&gt;Link Target&lt;/i&gt; is brought to the top of the report page.</sci:help>
									</sci:arg>
									<sci:arg name="Tooltip" type="StringType" required="false" visibility="visible" multi="false" uimpl="false">
										<sci:help>An optional tooltip for this reporting element.</sci:help>
									</sci:arg>
									<sci:arg name="HTML Attributes" type="HTMLAttributesType" required="false" visibility="visible" multi="false" uimpl="false">
										<sci:help>Defines attributes for the reporting element. These attributes can be used by JavaScript code that is &lt;a href=&quot;javascript:DoLink(&apos;{262A8E5D-BB8E-4dc4-A6F5-A61FC6047EC8}&apos;)&quot;&gt;embedded in&lt;/a&gt; or &lt;a href=&quot;javascript:DoLink(&apos;{6DF7D4FA-28BC-453b-8882-DE55C7CFFBF9}&apos;)&quot;&gt;included by&lt;/a&gt; the HTML report. One very common attribute is &quot;id&quot; which allows access to the element using the document.getElementById(id) method. Event handlers such as &quot;onclick&quot; and &quot;onmouseover&quot; are also common attributes.</sci:help>
										<sci:value>100</sci:value>
										<sci:value>class</sci:value>
										<sci:value>&apos;container&apos;;</sci:value>
									</sci:arg>
									<sci:arg name="Column Settings" type="GroupType" required="false" visibility="visible" multi="false" uimpl="false">
										<sci:help>Column settings control how the element appears when it is used inside a table.</sci:help>
										<sci:member>Column Settings Header Text</sci:member>
										<sci:member>Column Settings Header Format</sci:member>
										<sci:member>Column Settings Header Position</sci:member>
